definition.value: A monohydroxybenzoic acid having the hydroxy group at the 4-position together with a geranyl group at the 3-position.
Any alpha-amino acid ester that results from the formal condensation of the carboxylic acid group of L-alanine with an alcohol.
An organic disulfide consisting of two D-penicillamines joined by a disulfide bond.
Any straight-chain, C22 fatty acid having five C=C double bonds.
A methyl glycoside having beta-D-tyvelose as the glycoside component.
A hydrate that is the dihydrate form of succinylcholine chloride.

Hemicelluloses are polysaccharides in plant cell walls that have beta-(1->4)-linked backbones with an equatorial configuration. Hemicelluloses include xyloglucans, xylans, mannans and glucomannans, and beta-(1->3,1->4)-glucans.
An anthranilate obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 5-nitroanthranilic acid.
A monohydroxybenzoate that is obtained by removal of a proton from the carboxylic acid group of 5-nitrosalicylic acid.
A hydrate that is the trihydrate form of scopolamine hydrobromide.
An aminobenzoic acid in which the the amino group is ortho- to the carboxylic acid group, and which is substituted para- to the amino group by a nitro group.
A monohydroxybenzoic acid in which the hydroxy group is ortho- to the carboxylic acid group and which has a nitro substituent para- to the phenolic hydroxy group.
A nucleotide having guanine as the base.
A purine ribonucleotide where the purine is guanine.
A purine riboncleotide where adenine is the purine.
A heteroglycan in which a backbone composed of D-mannose units is substituted with D-glucose and/or D-galactose units.
A mannan consisting of repeating branched pentamannoside units joined via alpha-(1->6)-linkages.
A mannan consisting of repeating branched nonamannoside units joined via alpha-(1->6)-linkages.
A glycerate in which at least one of the hydroxy groups has been phosphorylated.
An chromium atom having a net electric charge.
A C20, straight-chain, polyunsaturated fatty acid anion containing five double bonds.
A dicarboxylate that contains four carbon atoms.
Any hydroxy carboxylic acid which contains a hydroxy group located beta- to the carboxylic acid group.
An unsaturated fatty acid anion that is the conjugate base of acetylenic fatty acid
Any cinnamic acid carrying one or more methoxy substituents.
A polymer, composed of poly(sulfide) macrmolecules.
A C18, saturated fatty acid composed of octadecanoic acid having an 11,12-methylene substituent forming a cyclopropane.
A polymer, composed of polyanion macromolecules.
A carbapenemcarboxylic acid that is the 3-carboxy derivative of 2,3-didehydro-1-carbapenam.
The five-membered ring form of D-fructose 6-phosphate.
A dipeptide consisting of L-glutamic acid having an L-alanyl attached to its alpha-amino group
A glycosylglucose in which the glycosyl moiety is L-rhamnose linked alpha to C-6 of D-glucose.
Any N-acetyl-D-glucosaminide having beta-configuration at the anomeric centre.
Any saponin derived from a hydroxysteroid.
Any benzoate anion carrying one or more amido substituents.
Any D-hexose 6-phosphate in which the hexose is in the pyranose form.
Any cyclitol having one or more alcoholic hydroxy groups replaced by substituted or unsubstituted amino groups.
Any organic molecular entity derived from a fatty acid.
A phosphocholine that is the 4-aminophenyl ester of choline phosphate.
An aldehyde in which the carbon alpha to the carbonyl group is part of a hydroxypolyether system.
A cyclodepsipeptide antibiotic, which is isolated from the filamentous fungus Aureobasidium pullulans R106 and is toxic to yeast at low concentrations (0.1-0.5 ug/ml).
A terpenoid in which one or more hydroxy functions are glycosylated.
A terpene glycoside in which the terpene moiety is a triterpenoid.
The five-membered ring form of L-arabinose.
Any derivative of 2-deoxystreptamine.
A phosphocholine linked to 6-hydroxyhexanoic acid via a phosphodiester linkage.
An ammonium betaine formed by deprotonation of the carboxylic acid group of 6-(O-phosphocholine)oxyhexanoic acid.
An ammonium betaine formed by deprotonation of the phosphoric acid group of 6-(O-phosphocholine)hydroxyhexanoic acid.
A 1,2-diacyl-sn-glycero-3-phosphocholine having palmitoyl and azelaoyl groups at positions 1 and 2 respectively.
